Practical 2: Assessing Primary School Coverage

GRID3

21 October 2020

This exercise provides an example of how we can use GRID3 data within a real-life application.

The problem: We want to assess education coverage for children in Primary schools in Lagos State. We are interested in finding out which areas are over-stretched with a high children of primary school age (5 -9) per school location. By identifying a target number of children per school, we can begin to highlight locations that may need further invention, such as expansion of existing schools all the addition of new schools.

Exercise Overview

Using geospatial analysis in R, this demo will show an assessment of education coverage for primary schools using the GRID3 population data for Lagos State.

In this exercise we are going to:

  1. Load some spatial data
  2. Subset the data to focus on points of interest
  3. Aggregate dataset using some basic geospatial techniques
  4. Try and identify connections between datasets to set targets

Loading Packages

require(sp)
require(sf)
require(raster)
require(dismo)
require(tmap)
require(dplyr)
require(DT)
require(rgdal)
require(deldir)

Step 1: Loading Datasets

We have four datasets used in this example:

These datasets can be obtained from the GRID3 Nigeria Data portal at https://grid3.gov.ng/

  1. School Locations locations:
  2. Ward boundaries
  3. Gridded population (children age 5-9) data for Lagos State
  4. State boundary
schools <- read.csv("data/lagos_schools.csv", fileEncoding="latin1")
population <- raster("data/lagos_pop_5_9.tif")
ward_boundaries <- st_read("data/lagos_wards.shp")
state_boundaries <- st_read("data/lagos_state.shp")

We will view our school location data below. In total there are schools recorded within the dataset. This includes data such as their location, whether the type of schools (primary, secondary), and whether it is private or publicly owned. An example of some of the data is shown below:

datatable(head(schools[6:12]),
          options = list(scrollX = TRUE)) # printing first rows of dataset

Step 2: Filtering Primary Schools

For our example, we are only interested in Primary schools. We will therefore filter the dataset below:

pri_school <- schools %>% filter(sub_type == "Primary")

Step 3: Create Point Data

In order to conduct spatial analysis on the data, we must convert these into a spatial object:

pri_school_pt <- st_as_sf(pri_school, coords = c("longitude", "latitude"))

We will quickly visualise this data below:

tmap_mode("view") # to make map interactive

tm_shape(pri_school_pt) +
  tm_dots(id = "name", col = "orange") +
  tm_shape(state_boundaries) +
  tm_borders(lwd = 3, col = "black") +
  tm_basemap("Esri.WorldImagery")

Visualise the gridded population data:

tm_shape(state_boundaries) +
  tm_borders(col = "black") +
  tm_shape(population) +
  tm_raster(title = "Population")

Step 4: Computing Voronoi Polygons

We are interested in finding out the primary school coverage across space.

  • Idea: optimize the partitioning of the area into polygons such that each polygon contains one health facility.
  • Method: Voronoi Polygon
voronoi <- dismo::voronoi(st_coordinates(pri_school_pt)) # compute voronoi from points coordinates
voronoi <- st_as_sf(voronoi) # convert into a "sf" object
voronoi <- cbind(voronoi, pri_school_pt)
st_crs(voronoi) <- st_crs(state_boundaries) # setting geographical coordinate system
voronoi <- voronoi %>% st_intersection(state_boundaries) # constrain polygon to state boundaries

Again, we will visualise these below:

tm_shape(voronoi) +
  tm_borders() +
  tm_shape(state_boundaries) +
  tm_borders(lwd = 3) +
  tm_shape(pri_school_pt) +
  tm_dots(col = "orange")

Step 5: Identifying Population Coverage Target with Zonal Statistics

Idea: find outliers in population per primary school to set a target.

Using Zonal statistics

Zonal statistic: summmary statistics of raster values at polygon level.

The Zonal statistic function requires more time than we have! Lets load the precalculation.

#zon.stat<-extract(population, voronoi, df=TRUE, fun=sum,na.rm=TRUE)
#pop_per_voronoi <- zon.stat
pop_per_voronoi <- readRDS("data/pop_per_voronoi")
datatable(head(pop_per_voronoi))

Setting a target

hist(pop_per_voronoi$lagos_pop_5_9,
  breaks = 50,
  main = "",
  xlab = "Population",
  col = "grey"
)
abline(v = 2000, col = "red")

Step 6: Identifying areas above target

We are subsetting the data to only include those voronois above the target that can be seen in orange. These would be recommended for further intervention, such as the expansion of existing schools or placement of new school locations.

voronoi <- voronoi %>% left_join(pop_per_voronoi, by = c("id" = "ID"))

above_target <- voronoi %>% filter(lagos_pop_5_9 > 2000)

tmap_mode("plot")
tm_shape(voronoi) +
  tm_borders() +
  tm_fill(col = "white") +
  tm_shape(above_target) +
  tm_borders() +
  tm_fill(col = "orange")
